<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Hardware on Andy Grunwald</title><link>https://andygrunwald.com/tags/hardware/</link><description>Recent content in Hardware on Andy Grunwald</description><generator>Hugo -- gohugo.io</generator><language>en-us</language><lastBuildDate>Sat, 18 Sep 2021 07:15:00 +0200</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://andygrunwald.com/tags/hardware/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>I can't wash my clothes without Open Source</title><link>https://andygrunwald.com/blog/i-cant-wash-my-clothes-without-open-source/</link><pubDate>Sat, 18 Sep 2021 07:15:00 +0200</pubDate><guid>https://andygrunwald.com/blog/i-cant-wash-my-clothes-without-open-source/</guid><description>&lt;p>My 20-year-old washing machine broke recently, and I bought a new one: A &lt;a href="https://www.siemens-home.bsh-group.com/de/produktliste/waeschepflege/waschmaschinen/frontlader/WM14VG43">Siemens iQ800 WM14VG43&lt;/a>.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>The manual contained a sheet of paper headlining &lt;a href="https://andygrunwald.com/files/information-regarding-open-source-software.pdf">&lt;strong>Information regarding Open Source Software&lt;/strong>&lt;/a>.
Four software projects have been listed: &lt;a href="https://andygrunwald.com/blog/i-cant-wash-my-clothes-without-open-source/#openbsd">OpenBSD&lt;/a>, &lt;a href="https://andygrunwald.com/blog/i-cant-wash-my-clothes-without-open-source/#tropicssl">TropicSSL&lt;/a>, &lt;a href="https://andygrunwald.com/blog/i-cant-wash-my-clothes-without-open-source/#flexible-and-economical-utf-8-decoder">Flexible and Economical UTF-8 Decoder&lt;/a>, and &lt;a href="https://andygrunwald.com/blog/i-cant-wash-my-clothes-without-open-source/#the-wide-project">the WIDE project&lt;/a>.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>things with buzzers: building your own game-show buzzers</title><link>https://andygrunwald.com/blog/things-with-buzzers-building-your-own-game-show-buzzers/</link><pubDate>Fri, 01 Nov 2019 12:00:00 +0100</pubDate><guid>https://andygrunwald.com/blog/things-with-buzzers-building-your-own-game-show-buzzers/</guid><description>&lt;p>&lt;strong>tl;dr&lt;/strong>: We built custom game show buzzers, wrote a WebSocket server, and connected them to various applications.
Finally, we documented and open-sourced everything. Check out the &lt;strong>things with buzzers&lt;/strong> series &lt;em>&lt;a href="https://github.com/andygrunwald/things-with-buzzers-hardware" title="things with buzzers hardware at GitHub">hardware&lt;/a>&lt;/em>, &lt;em>&lt;a href="https://github.com/andygrunwald/things-with-buzzers-websocket" title="things with buzzers WebSocket software at GitHub">websocket&lt;/a>&lt;/em> and a frontend like &lt;em>&lt;a href="https://github.com/andygrunwald/things-with-buzzers-jeopardy" title="things with buzzers Jeopardy! game software at GitHub">Jeopardy!&lt;/a>&lt;/em>.
Start today, and build your own!&lt;/p></description></item></channel></rss>